name: structural timber production | structural timber | Cutoff, U
description:
ecoQuery: https://ecoquery.ecoinvent.org/3.10/cutoff/dataset/22640/documentation

This dataset represents the production of structural timber in Europe. Data are based on a sample of German production.;Structural timber is a building material with precisely defined product characteristics, which was developed specially to meet the high requirements of modern timber construction. Structural timber is a kiln-dried, strength-graded, and in most cases finger-jointed timber product made of solid softwood. Thanks to the method of cutting used and the low moisture content of the material it has little propensity for cracking, is dimensionally stable and, subject to due observance of the rules relating to the structural protection of wood, can also be used without wood preservatives. Structural timber is available in a wide range of preferred dimensions and wood types (spruce, fir, pine, larch or Douglas fir) with precisely defined surface finishes.;Reference:;Rüter, S. and S. Diederichs (2012): Ökobilanz-Basisdaten für Bauprodukte aus Holz. Arbeitsbericht aus dem Institut für Holztechnologie und Holzbiologie Nr. 2012/1, Johann Heinrich von Thünen-Institut (vTI), Hamburg. ;[This dataset is meant to replace the following datasets:]

From the reception at the factory gate of all materials and fuels used.

This activity ends with the structural timber produced at the factory gate. The dataset includes the inputs to and outputs of the production processes and the available process emissions. Infrastructure is a rough estimate.

exchanges.description:
Reference product. Plywood produced in Germany by processes representative for global average. The reference product is ready for delivery at the wooden board factory. 
A large number of materials can be produced with differing properties and areas of use. Typical uses are as construction plywood for wall, floor, and ceiling panels and also as panels for concrete shuttering, and decorative covering veneers in interior furnishings (e.g. wall panels or doors).
